===Anime===
The manga was adapted into a 3-episode [[original video animation]] by [[Daume|Doumu]]. The anime is licensed in the United States by Sentai Filmworks and distributed by [[A.D. Vision#ADV Films|ADV Films]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-08-10/adv-gets-indian-summer-anime-five-live-action-titles|title=ADV Gets ''Indian Summer'' Anime, Five Live-Action Titles|date=2008-08-10|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> However, with ADV being shut down, distribution was now handled by [[Section23 Films]]. It was also distributed in Russia by MC Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mc-ent.ru/anime.html|title=<U+041C><U+041E><U+0419> <U+041B><U+042E><U+0411><U+0418><U+041C><U+042B><U+0419> <U+0420><U+041E><U+0411><U+041E><U+0422>|trans_title=''Koharu Biyori''|publisher=MC Entertainment|language=Russian|accessdate=27 November 2009}}</ref> The episodes were released in Japan between October 14, 2007 and April 2, 2008.

[[Geneon]] released 3 DVDs in Japan. The first DVD was released on November 21, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000VT9V4Q/ |title=<U+3053><U+306F><U+308B><U+3073><U+3088><U+308A> 1 [DVD]|publisher=[[Amazon.co.jp]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref> The second DVD was released on February 8, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000VT9V50/ |title=<U+3053><U+306F><U+308B><U+3073><U+3088><U+308A> 2 [DVD]|publisher=[[Amazon.co.jp]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref> The final DVD was released on April 2, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/B000VT9V5A/ |title=<U+3053><U+306F><U+308B><U+3073><U+3088><U+308A> 3 [DVD]|publisher=[[Amazon.co.jp]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=2009-03-21}}</ref> The subtitled series was released on March 10, 2009 in the US, there is no English-dubbed version available.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Indian-Summer-Complete-Collection/dp/B001PSUM04/|title=Indian Summer: Complete Collection|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=2013-11-16}}</ref>

The [[original video animation]]s use three pieces of [[theme music]]. {{nihongo|"Apron dake wa Toranaide!"|<U+30A8><U+30D7><U+30ED><U+30F3><U+3060><U+3051><U+306F><U+53D6><U+3089><U+306A><U+3044><U+3067>!}} by [[Eri Kitamura]] is the series' opening theme, while {{nihongo|"Love Song Kamo Shirenai"|<U+30E9><U+30D6><U+30BD><U+30F3><U+30B0><U+304B><U+3082><U+3057><U+308C><U+306A><U+3044>|Rabusongu Kamo Shire Nai}}  by [[Eri Kitamura]] and [[Satomi Akesaka]] is the ending theme for the first two episodes. {{nihongo|"Hora, Attan Kanan Desu"|<U+307B><U+3089>, <U+3042><U+3063><U+305F><U+3093><U+304B><U+306A><U+3093><U+3067><U+3059>}} by [[Eri Kitamura]] is the ending theme for the third episode.

